{
  "texts": [
    "Remark 1.6.",
    "We take this opportunity to summarize the situation of our interest in Table 1: Let A be an abelian variety (not semiabelian, for simplicity) of dimension g ≥ 1 defined over a finitely generated field k of characteristic zero, and K an algebraic extension of k. We denote by A(K) tor the torsion subgroup (classical)",
    "We know that the field k(σ) is located in one of the three cells shown in the table for almost all σ ∈ G k (by [FreJ74, Zyw16, JP19]), but do not know which one it is in.",
    "b For m = (m p) p with m p ≥ 1 for infinitely many p and A of dimension ≤ g with rank(A(k)) ≥ 1 (by Theorem 1.2 (= Theorem 2.3) and Proposition 1.3 (= Proposition 2.4)).",
    "c Larsen [Lar05] proved that A(K) ∼ = M ⊕ (Q/Z) ⊕2g for any abelian variety A over k of dimension g, where K = k(A(k) tor) and M is a free Z-module, and proved that rank(M) = ∞ if A is an elliptic curve (the result for the case where k = Q and A is an elliptic curve was independently obtained by Habegger [Hab13])."
  ]
}